text: You were right to seperate the doors as this is how it is in reality, and how it would be expected in a studio

Your first issue is something that we always look at how people handle it. You say the edge loops go all the way around the model, but they don't have to. What you need to learn is how to terminate edges when they are not needed any more or you will always run in to this issue.
I'll draw something in a little bit to demonstrate
you want to keep things quads and avoid triangles as much as possible

Your problem with the door is coming from the fact that your edges with the train do not line up. You will never get the same curve if they do not line up. This is one of the more complex things to get right, and takes some mastering, but it can always be done
It is difficult to tell what is going on with the windows in your image
but here is somethig to think about
Ah, I see, thanks. I'll try fixing it now.

basically, these types of problem will be coming up in every model you make. And there are hundreds of creative ways to solve the issue, you will see lots of people finding different solutions to the same problem. This is where the most creative part of hard surface modelling will come in, each problem will be different and you will need to try find clever and interesting ways to solve the issue
It's not something that can be taught so much, but something that you learn simply by experiencing the issue, and persevering through it to find a solution
Its tough at first but it gets easier with experience

thanks for showing me what its meant to look like, it's actually extremely helpful. And yes, i agree, this is quite fun because it's like creative problem solving (as long as you know what you're doing).
